2026-03-19 | Largest BST in Binary Tree

	Question
Return the size (number of nodes) of the largest BST subtree.

	Approach
We solve using **postorder traversal (bottom-up)**.

For each node, return:
		1. isBST → whether subtree is BST
		2. size → size of subtree if BST
		3. min → minimum value in subtree
		4. max → maximum value in subtree

Steps:
1.	Traverse left and right.
2.	Check BST condition:
		left.max < root.val < right.min
3.	If valid:
		size = left.size + right.size + 1
		update global max
4.	If invalid:
		mark as not BST

Why postorder?
Because we need information from children before deciding for parent.

	Time Complexity
	O(n)

	Space Complexity
	O(h)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:

    int maxSize = 0;

    struct NodeInfo {
        bool isBST;
        int size;
        int minVal;
        int maxVal;
    };

    NodeInfo dfs(TreeNode* root) {

        if (!root)
            return {true, 0, INT_MAX, INT_MIN};

        auto left = dfs(root->left);
        auto right = dfs(root->right);

        NodeInfo curr;

        if (left.isBST && right.isBST &&
            root->val > left.maxVal &&
            root->val < right.minVal) {

            curr.isBST = true;
            curr.size = left.size + right.size + 1;
            curr.minVal = min(root->val, left.minVal);
            curr.maxVal = max(root->val, right.maxVal);

            maxSize = max(maxSize, curr.size);
        }
        else {
            curr.isBST = false;
            curr.size = 0;
            curr.minVal = INT_MIN;
            curr.maxVal = INT_MAX;
        }

        return curr;
    }

    int largestBst(TreeNode* root) {
        dfs(root);
        return maxSize;
    }
};

	Key Insight
Each node decides:
“Am I root of a BST?”

Using:
		left subtree info + right subtree info

This avoids rechecking subtrees repeatedly → O(n) optimal solution.
